Even knowing the size of terminal matters here so even there's a algorithm for it 

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/ioctl.h>

int main() {
    struct winsize w;
    ioctl(0, TIOCGWINSZ, &w);
    printf("rows: %d\n", w.ws_row);
    printf("cols: %d\n", w.ws_col);
    return 0;
}
```
this always will be the same code for any program


## this is what each line does  
struct winsize w       — declares a container to hold the terminal size
ioctl(0, TIOCGWINSZ, &w)  — asks OS to fill that container with dimensions
w.ws_row               — the rows value inside the container
w.ws_col               — the cols value inside the container

1. include the sys/ioctl.h header
2. make a variable with struct winsize as datatype
3. ioctl function sends the terminal size data to the variable 
4. the arguments of ioctl function is :
				   0 for stdin , which is terminal 
				   tiocgwinsz indicates the sentence :
				      TIOC    —  Terminal Input Output Control
					  G       —  Get
					  WIN     —  Window
                      SZ      —  Size
                    var_name with & addressing operator 
 5.  the data is stored in var_name.ws_row and var_name.ws_col


